# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: one-watt-initiative
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A **carbon footprint** (or **greenhouse gas footprint**) is a calculated value or index that makes it possible to compare the total amount of greenhouse gases that an activity, product, company or country adds to the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints are usually reported in tonnes of emissions (CO2-equivalent) per unit of comparison.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Such units can be, for example, *tonnes CO2-eq per year*, *per kilogram of protein for consumption*, *per kilometer travelled*, *per piece of clothing* and so forth.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A product's carbon footprint includes the emissions for the entire life cycle.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These run from the production along the supply chain to its final consumption and disposal.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Similarly, an organization's carbon footprint includes the direct as well as the indirect emissions that it causes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol (for carbon accounting of organizations) calls these *Scope 1, 2 and 3 emissions*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] There are several methodologies and online tools to calculate the carbon footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They depend on whether the focus is on a country, organization, product or individual person.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For example, the carbon footprint of a product could help consumers decide which product to buy if they want to be climate aware.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For climate change mitigation activities, the carbon footprint can help distinguish those economic activities with a high footprint from those with a low footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] So the carbon footprint concept allows everyone to make comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It also helps people devise strategies and priorities for reducing the carbon footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2eq) emissions per unit of comparison is a suitable way to express a carbon footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This sums up all the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It includes all greenhouse gases, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] And it looks at emissions from economic activities, events, organizations and services.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In some definitions, only the carbon dioxide emissions are taken into account.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These do not include other greenhouse gases, such as methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Various methods to calculate the carbon footprint exist, and these may differ somewhat for different entities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For organizations it is common practice to use the Greenhouse Gas Protocol.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It includes three carbon emission scopes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 1 refers to *direct* carbon emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 and 3 refer to *indirect* carbon emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are those indirect emissions that result from the activities of an organization but come from sources which they do not own or control.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For countries it is common to use consumption-based emissions accounting to calculate their carbon footprint for a given year.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting using input-output analysis backed by super-computing makes it possible to analyse global supply chains.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Countries also prepare national GHG inventories for the UNFCCC.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The GHG emissions listed in those national inventories are only from activities in the country itself.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This approach is called *territorial-based accounting* or *production-based accounting.* It does not take into account production of goods and services imported on behalf of residents.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] *Consumption-based accounting* does reflect emissions from goods and services imported from other countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting is therefore more comprehensive.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This comprehensive carbon footprint reporting including Scope 3 emissions deals with gaps in current systems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Countries' GHG inventories for the UNFCCC do not include international transport.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Comprehensive carbon footprint reporting looks at the final demand for emissions, to where the consumption of the goods and services takes place.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scientists report carbon footprints in terms of equivalents of tonnes of CO2 emissions (CO2-equivalent).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They may report them per year, per person, per kilogram of protein, per kilometer travelled, and so on.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In the definition of carbon footprint, some scientists include only CO2.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] But more commonly they include several of the notable greenhouse gases.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They can compare various greenhouse gases by using carbon dioxide equivalents over a relevant time scale, like 100 years.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Some organizations use the term *greenhouse gas footprint* or *climate footprint* to emphasize that all greenhouse gases are included, not just carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Greenhouse Gas Protocol includes all of the most important greenhouse gases.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In comparison, the IPCC definition of *carbon footprint* in 2022 covers only carbon dioxide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] That publication included only carbon dioxide in the definition of carbon footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It justified this with the argument that other greenhouse gases were more difficult to quantify.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is because of their differing global warming potentials.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They also stated that an inclusion of all greenhouse gases would make the carbon footprint indicator less practical.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] But there are disadvantages to this approach.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] One disadvantage of not including methane is that some products or sectors that have a high methane footprint such as livestock appear less harmful for the climate than they actually are.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The greenhouse gas protocol is a set of standards for tracking greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The standards divide emissions into three *scopes (S*cope 1, 2 and 3) within the value chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions caused directly by the organization such as by burning fossil fuels are referred to as S*cope 1*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Emissions caused indirectly by an organization, such as by purchasing secondary energy sources like electricity, heat, cooling or steam are called *Scope 2*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Lastly, indirect emissions associated with upstream or downstream processes are called *Scope 3*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Direct or *Scope 1* carbon emissions come from sources on the site that is producing a product or delivering a service.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] An example for industry would be the emissions from burning a fuel on site.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] On the individual level, emissions from personal vehicles or gas-burning stoves are Scope 1.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Indirect carbon emissions are emissions from sources upstream or downstream from the process being studied.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They are also known as *Scope 2* or *Scope 3* emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 2 emissions are the indirect emissions related to purchasing electricity, heat, or steam used on site.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Examples of upstream carbon emissions include transportation of materials and fuels, any energy used outside of the production facility, and waste produced outside the production facility.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Examples of downstream carbon emissions include any end-of-life process or treatments, product and waste transportation, and emissions associated with selling the product.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol says it is important to calculate upstream and downstream emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emissions are all other indirect emissions derived from the activities of an organization.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] But they are from sources they do not own or control.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The GHG Protocol's *Corporate Value Chain (Scope 3) Accounting and Reporting Standard* allows companies to assess their entire value chain emissions impact and identify where to focus reduction activities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scope 3 emission sources include emissions from suppliers and product users.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These are also known as the *value chain*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Transportation of goods, and other indirect emissions are also part of this scope.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In 2022 about 30% of US companies reported Scope 3 emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board is developing a recommendation to include Scope 3 emissions in all GHG reporting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The current rise in global average temperature is more rapid than previous changes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is primarily caused by humans burning fossil fuels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The increase in greenhouse gases in the atmosphere is also due to deforestation and agricultural and industrial practices.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The two most notable greenhouse gases are carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions, and hence humanity's carbon footprint, have been increasing during the 21st century.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions enough to limit the rise in global temperature to no more than 1.5 °C above pre-industrial levels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint concept makes comparisons between the climate impacts of individuals, products, companies and countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint label on products could enable consumers to choose products with a lower carbon footprint if they want to help limit climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For meat products, as an example, such a label could make it clear that beef has a higher carbon footprint than chicken.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Understanding the size of an organization's carbon footprint makes it possible to devise a strategy to reduce it.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For most businesses the vast majority of emissions do not come from activities on site, known as Scope 1, or from energy supplied to the organization, known as Scope 2, but from Scope 3 emissions, the extended upstream and downstream supply chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Therefore, ignoring Scope 3 emissions makes it impossible to detect all emissions of importance, which limits options for mitigation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Large companies in sectors such as clothing or automobiles would need to examine more than 100,000 supply chain pathways to fully report their carbon footprints.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The importance of displacement of carbon emissions has been known for some years.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scientists also call this carbon leakage.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The idea of a carbon footprint addresses concerns of carbon leakage which the Paris Agreement does not cover.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage occurs when importing countries outsource production to exporting countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The outsourcing countries are often rich countries while the exporters are often low-income countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Countries can make it appear that their GHG emissions are falling by moving "dirty" industries abroad, even if their emissions could be increasing when looked at from a consumption perspective.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon leakage and related international trade have a range of environmental impacts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These include increased air pollution, water scarcity, biodiversity loss, raw material usage, and energy depletion.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Scholars have argued in favour of using both consumption-based and production-based accounting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This helps establish shared producer and consumer responsibility.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Currently countries report on their annual GHG inventory to the UNFCCC based on their territorial emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is known as the territorial-based or production-based approach.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Including consumption-based calculations in the UNFCCC reporting requirements would help close loopholes by addressing the challenge of carbon leakage.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Paris Agreement currently does not require countries to include in their national totals GHG emissions associated with international transport.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These emissions are reported separately.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They are not subject to the limitation and reduction commitments of Annex 1 Parties under the Climate Convention and Kyoto Protocol.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint methodology includes GHG emissions associated with international transport, thereby assigning emissions caused by international trade to the importing country.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The calculation of the carbon footprint of a product, service or sector requires expert knowledge and careful examination of what is to be included.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon footprints can be calculated at different scales.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They can apply to whole countries, cities, neighborhoods and also sectors, companies and products.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Several free online carbon footprint calculators exist to calculate personal carbon footprints.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Software such as the "Scope 3 Evaluator" can help companies report emissions throughout their value chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The software tools can help consultants and researchers to model global sustainability footprints.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In each situation there are a number of questions that need to be answered.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These include which activities are linked to which emissions, and which proportion should be attributed to which company.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Software is essential for company management.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] But there is a need for new ways of enterprise resource planning to improve corporate sustainability performance.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] To achieve 95% carbon footprint coverage, it would be necessary to assess 12 million individual supply-chain contributions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is based on analyzing 12 sectoral case studies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Scope 3 calculations can be made easier using input-output analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is a technique originally developed by Nobel Prize-winning economist Wassily Leontief.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emission accounting traces the impacts of demand for goods and services along the global supply chain to the end-consumer.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is also called consumption-based carbon accounting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In contrast, a *production-based approach* to calculating GHG emissions is not a carbon footprint analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This approach is also called a *territorial-based approach.* The production-based approach includes only impacts physically produced in the country in question.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based accounting redistributes the emissions from production-based accounting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It considers that emissions in another country are necessary for the home country's consumption bundle.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumer-based accounting is based on input-output analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is used at the highest levels for any economic research question related to environmental or social impacts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Analysis of global supply chains is possible using consumption-based accounting with input-output analysis assisted by super-computing capacity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Leontief created Input-output analysis (IO) to demonstrate the relationship between consumption and production in an economy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It incorporates the entire supply chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output tables from countries' national accounts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It also uses international data such as UN Comtrade and Eurostat.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has been extended globally to multi-regional input-output analysis (MRIO).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Innovations and technology enabling the analysis of billions of supply chains made this possible.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Standards set by the United Nations underpin this analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The analysis enables a *Structural Path Analysis.* This scans and ranks the top supply chain nodes and paths.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It conveniently lists hotspots for urgent action.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Input-output analysis has increased in popularity because of its ability to examine global value chains.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Life cycle assessment (LCA) is a methodology for assessing all environmental impacts associated with the life cycle of a commercial product, process, or service.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is not limited to the greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It includes water pollution, air pollution, ecotoxicity and similar types of pollution.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Some widely recognized procedures for LCA are included in the ISO 14000 series of environmental management standards.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A standard called ISO 14040:2006 provides the framework for conducting an LCA study.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] ISO 14060 family of standards provides further sophisticated tools.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Also the latest standard, ISO 14064:2018 has the right set of tools that will help reduce Carbon Emissions in Corporations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These are used to quantify, monitor, report and validate or verify GHG emissions and removals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas product life cycle assessments can also comply with specifications such as Publicly Available Specification (PAS) 2050 and the GHG Protocol Life Cycle Accounting and Reporting Standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] An advantage of LCA is the high level of detail that can be obtained on-site or by liaising with suppliers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] However, LCA has been hampered by the artificial construction of a boundary after which no further impacts of upstream suppliers are considered.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This can introduce significant truncation errors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] LCA has been combined with input-output analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This enables on-site detailed knowledge to be incorporated.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] IO connects to global economic databases to incorporate the entire supply chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Critics argue that the original aim of promoting the personal carbon footprint concept was to shift responsibility away from corporations and institutions and on to personal lifestyle choices.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The fossil fuel company BP ran a large advertising campaign for the personal carbon footprint in 2004 which helped popularize this concept.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This strategy, employed by many major fossil fuel companies, has been criticized for trying to shift the blame for negative consequences of those industries on to individual choices.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Geoffrey Supran and Naomi Oreskes of Harvard University argue that concepts such as carbon footprints "hamstring us, and they put blinders on us, to the systemic nature of the climate crisis and the importance of taking collective action to address the problem".
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] While the focus on individual behaviour has shaped public discourse, scientific assessments emphasize that this approach alone is insufficient.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The IPCC notes that individual behavioural changes alone are insufficient to achieve deep emission reductions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Reducing emissions through behaviour is important, but eliminating combustion altogether through systemic change is critical to long-term climate goals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A focus on carbon footprints can lead people to ignore or even exacerbate other related environmental issues of concern.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These include biodiversity loss, ecotoxicity, and habitat destruction.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It may not be easy to measure these other human impacts on the environment with a single indicator like the carbon footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumers may think that the carbon footprint is a proxy for environmental impact.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] There can be trade-offs between reducing carbon footprint and environmental protection goals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] One example is the use of biofuel, a renewable energy source that can reduce the carbon footprint of the energy supply but can also pose ecological challenges during its production.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is because it is often produced in monocultures with ample use of fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Another example is offshore wind parks, which could have unintended impacts on marine ecosystems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint analysis solely focuses on greenhouse gas emissions, unlike a life-cycle assessment which is much broader and looks at all environmental impacts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Therefore, it is useful to stress in communication activities that the carbon footprint is just one in a family of indicators (e.g. ecological footprint, water footprint, land footprint, and material footprint), and should not be looked at in isolation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In fact, carbon footprint can be treated as one component of ecological footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The "Sustainable Consumption and Production Hotspot Analysis Tool" (SCP-HAT) is a tool to place carbon footprint analysis into a wider perspective.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It includes a number of socio-economic and environmental indicators.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It offers calculations that are either consumption-based, following the carbon footprint approach, or production-based.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The database of the SCP-HAT tool is underpinned by input–output analysis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This means it includes Scope 3 emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The IO methodology is also governed by UN standards.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is based on input-output tables of countries' national accounts and international trade data such as UN Comtrade, and therefore it is comparable worldwide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* has been applied to limited calculations that do not include Scope 3 emissions or the entire supply chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This can lead to claims of misleading customers with regards to the real carbon footprints of companies or products.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Greenhouse gas emissions (GHG emissions) from human activities intensify the greenhouse effect which contributes to climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide (CO2) from burning fossil fuels (such as coal, oil, and natural gas) is the main cause of climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The largest annual emissions are from China followed by the United States, which has higher emissions per capita.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The main producers fueling the emissions globally are large oil and gas companies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Emissions from human activities have increased atmospheric carbon dioxide by about 50% over pre-industrial levels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The growing levels of emissions have varied, but have been consistent among all greenhouse gases.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Over 60 billion tons were emitted in 2025, higher than any year before.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Total cumulative emissions from 1870 to 2022 were 703 GtC (2575 GtCO2), of which 484±20 GtC (1773±73 GtCO2) from fossil fuels and industry, and 219±60 GtC (802±220 GtCO2) from land use change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Land-use change, such as deforestation, caused about 31% of cumulative emissions over 1870–2022, coal 32%, oil 24%, and gas 10%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon dioxide is the main greenhouse gas resulting from human activities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It accounts for more than half of warming.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Methane (CH4) emissions have almost the same short-term impact.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Nitrous oxide (N2O) and fluorinated gases (F-gases) play a lesser role in comparison.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Emissions of carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide in 2023 were all higher than ever before.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The Carbon Trust has worked with UK manufacturers to produce "thousands of carbon footprint assessments".
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] As of 2014 the Carbon Trust state they have measured 28,000 certifiable product carbon footprints.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This NGO has also developed a labelling scheme which "supports informed consumer choices and business procurement decisions".
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Plant-based foods tend to have a lower carbon footprint than meat and dairy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This holds true when comparing the footprint of foods in terms of their weight, protein content or calories.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The protein output of peas and beef provides an example.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Producing 100 grams of protein from peas emits just 0.4 kilograms of carbon dioxide equivalents (CO2eq).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] To get the same amount of protein from beef, emissions would be nearly 90 times higher, at 35 kgCO2eq.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Only a small fraction of the carbon footprint of food comes from transport and packaging.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Most of it comes from processes on the farm, or from land use change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This means the choice of what to eat has a larger potential to reduce carbon footprint than how far the food has traveled, or how much packaging it is wrapped in.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report found that global GHG emissions have continued to rise across all sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The most rapid growth was in transport and industry.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A key driver of global carbon emissions is affluence.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The IPCC noted that the wealthiest 10% in the world contribute between about one third to one half (36%–45%) of global GHG emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Researchers have previously found that affluence is the key driver of carbon emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It has a bigger impact than population growth.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] And it counters the effects of technological developments.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Continued economic growth mirrors the increasing trend in material extraction and GHG emissions**.** "Industrial emissions have been growing faster since 2000 than emissions in any other sector, driven by increased basic materials extraction and production," the IPCC said.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] There can be wide variations in emissions for transport of people.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They include the length of the trip, the source of electricity in the local grid and the occupancy of public transport.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In the case of driving the type of vehicle and number of passengers are factors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Over short to medium distances, walking or cycling are nearly always the lowest carbon way to travel.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint of cycling one kilometer is usually in the range of 16 to 50 grams CO2eq per km.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For moderate or long distances, trains nearly always have a lower carbon footprint than other options.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon accounting, also called greenhouse gas accounting or GHG accounting, is a framework of methods to measure and track how much greenhouse gas (GHG) an organization emits.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It can also be used to track projects or actions to reduce emissions in sectors such as forestry or renewable energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Corporations, cities and other groups use these techniques to help limit climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Organizations will often set an emissions baseline, create targets for reducing emissions, and track progress towards them.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The accounting methods enable them to do this in a more consistent and transparent manner.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The main reasons for GHG accounting are to address social responsibility concerns or meet legal requirements.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Public rankings of companies, financial due diligence and potential cost savings are other reasons.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] GHG accounting methods help investors better understand the climate risks of companies they invest in.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They also help with net zero emission goals of corporations or communities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Many governments around the world require various forms of reporting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] There is some evidence that programs that require GHG accounting help to lower emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Markets for buying and selling carbon credits depend on accurate measurement of emissions and emission reductions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These techniques can help to understand the impacts of specific products and services.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] They do this by quantifying their GHG emissions throughout their lifecycle (carbon footprint).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] CO2 emissions of countries are typically measured on the basis of *production*.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This accounting method is sometimes referred to as *territorial emissions.* Countries use it when they report their emissions, and set domestic and international targets such as Nationally Determined Contributions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] *Consumption*-based emissions on the other hand are adjusted for trade.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] To calculate consumption-based emissions analysts have to track which goods are traded across the world.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Whenever a product is imported, all CO2 emissions that were emitted in the production of that product are included.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Consumption-based emissions reflect the lifestyle choices of a country's citizens.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] According to the World Bank, the global average carbon footprint in 2014 was about 5 tonnes of CO2 per person, measured on a production basis.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The EU average for 2007 was about 13.8 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] For the USA, Luxembourg and Australia it was over 25 tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In 2017, the average for the USA was about 20 metric tonnes CO2e per person.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This is one of the highest per capita figures in the world.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The footprints per capita of countries in Africa and India were well below average.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Assuming a global population of around 9–10 billion by 2050, a carbon footprint of about 2–2.5 tonnes CO2e per capita is needed to stay within a 2 °C target.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] These carbon footprint calculations are based on a consumption-based approach using a Multi-Regional Input-Output (MRIO) database.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This database accounts for all greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in the global supply chain and allocates them to the final consumer of the purchased commodities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Efforts to reduce the carbon footprint of products, services, and organizations help limit climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Such activities are called climate change mitigation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation, also called decarbonisation, is an action to limit the greenhouse gases in the atmosphere that cause climate change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Climate change mitigation actions include conserving energy and replacing fossil fuels with clean energy sources.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Secondary mitigation strategies include changes to land use and removing carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] 2022 assessments emphasize that global greenhouse gas emissions must peak before 2025 and decline by about 43% by 2030 to limit warming to 1.5 °C, requiring rapid transitions in energy, transport, and land-use systems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Carbon offsetting can reduce a company's overall carbon footprint by providing it with a carbon credit.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] This compensates the company for carbon dioxide emissions by recognizing an equivalent reduction of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Reforestation, or restocking existing forests that have previously been depleted, is an example of carbon offsetting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] A carbon footprint study can identify specific and critical areas for improvement.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It uses input-output analysis and scrutinizes the entire supply chain.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Such an analysis could be used to eliminate the supply chains with the highest greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The term *carbon footprint* was first used in a BBC vegetarian food magazine in 1999, though the broader concept of *ecological footprint*, which encompasses the carbon footprint, had been used since at least 1992, as also chronicled by journalist William Safire in the New York Times.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] In 2005, fossil fuel company BP hired the large advertising campaign Ogilvy to popularize the idea of a carbon footprint for individuals.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The campaign instructed people to calculate their personal footprints and provided ways for people to "go on a low-carbon diet".
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint is derived from the ecological footprint, which encompasses carbon emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The carbon footprint follows the logic of ecological footprint accounting, which tracks the resource use embodied in consumption, whether it is a product, an individual, a city, or a country.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] While in the ecological footprint, carbon emissions are translated into areas needed to absorb the carbon emissions, the carbon footprint on its own is expressed in the weight of carbon emissions per time unit.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] William Rees wrote the first academic publication about ecological footprints in 1992.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] Other related concepts from the 1990s are the "ecological backpack" and material input per unit of service (MIPS).
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The International Sustainability Standards Board (ISSB) aims to bring global, rigorous oversight to carbon footprint reporting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It was formed out of the International Financial Reporting Standards.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It will require companies to report on their Scope 3 emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The ISSB has taken on board criticisms of other initiatives in its aims for universality.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It consolidates the Carbon Disclosure Standards Board, the Sustainability Accounting Standards Board and the Value Reporting Foundation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It complements the Global Reporting Initiative.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] It is influenced by the Task Force on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] As of early 2023, Great Britain and Nigeria were preparing to adopt these standards.
[src:one-watt-initiative/carbon-footprint] The *Expanded Total Equivalent Warming Impact* method has been used for an accurate evaluation of refrigerators emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] The **Department for Business, Innovation and Skills** (**BIS**) was a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] It was created by the Gordon Brown premiership on 5 June 2009 by the merger of the Department for Innovation, Universities and Skills and the Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] It was disbanded by the Theresa May premiership on the creation of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on 14 July 2016.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] The Permanent Secretary was Sir Martin Donnelly.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] Some policies apply to England alone due to devolution, while others are not devolved and therefore apply to other nations of the United Kingdom.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] Economic policy is mostly devolved but several important policy areas are reserved to Westminster.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] Further and higher education policy is mostly devolved.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] Reserved and excepted matters are outlined below.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] The Scottish Government Economy and Education Directorates handle devolved economic and further and higher education policy respectively.
[src:one-watt-initiative/department-for-business-innovation-and-skills] Under the Welsh devolution settlement, specific policy areas are transferred to the Welsh Government rather than reserved to Westminster.
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] On 6 January 2010 the **European Commission Regulation No.
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] 1275/2008** came into force regulating requirements for standby and off mode electric power consumption of electrical and electronic household and office equipment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] This regulation arises from the One Watt Initiative by the International Energy Agency (IEA).
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] The regulations mandate that from 6 January 2010 "off mode" and standby power shall not exceed 1W, "standby plus" power (providing information or status display in addition to possible reactivation function) shall not exceed 2W.
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] Equipment must where appropriate provide off mode and/or standby mode when the equipment is connected to the mains power source.
[src:one-watt-initiative/ec-regulation-1275-2008] These figures were halved on 6 January 2013.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Green engineering practices improve the life cycle of the components of machines which convert energy from one form into another.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Observing appliance usage, establishing an energy usage profile, and revealing energy consumption patterns in circumstances where energy is used poorly, can pinpoint user habits and behaviors in energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Appliance energy profiling helps identify inefficient appliances with high energy consumption and energy load.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Seasonal variations also greatly influence energy load, as more air-conditioning is used in warmer seasons and heating in colder seasons.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Achieving a balance between energy load and user comfort is complex yet essential for energy preservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] On a large scale, a few factors affect energy consumption trends, including political issues, technological developments, economic growth, and environmental concerns.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] User behavior has a significant effect on energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It involves user activity detection, profiling, and appliance interaction behaviors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] User profiling consists of the identification of energy usage patterns of the user and replacing required system settings with automated settings that can be initiated on request.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Within user profiling, personal characteristics are instrumental in affecting energy conservation behavior.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These characteristics include household income, education, gender, age, and social norms.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] User behavior also relies on the impact of personality traits, social norms, and attitudes on energy conservation behavior.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Beliefs and attitudes toward a convenient lifestyle, environmentally friendly transport, energy security, and residential location choices affect energy conservation behavior.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, energy conservation can be made possible by adopting pro-environmental behavior and energy-efficient systems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Education on approaches to energy conservation can result in wise energy use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The choices made by the users yield energy usage patterns.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Rigorous analysis of these usage patterns identifies waste energy patterns, and improving those patterns may reduce significant energy load.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Therefore, human behavior is critical to determining the implications of energy conservation measures and solving environmental problems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Substantial energy conservation may be achieved if users' habit loops are modified.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] User habits significantly impact energy demand; thus, providing recommendations for improving user habits contributes to energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Micro-moments are essential in realizing energy consumption patterns and are identified using a variety of sensing units positioned in prominent areas across the home.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The micro-moment is an event that changes the state of the appliance from inactive to active and helps in building users' energy consumption profiles according to their activities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation can be achieved through user habits by following energy-saving recommendations at micro-moments.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Unnecessary energy usage can be decreased by selecting a suitable schedule for appliance operation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Creating an effective scheduling system requires an understanding of user habits regarding appliances.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Many techniques for energy conservation comprise off-peak scheduling, which means operating an appliance in a low-price energy hour.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This schedule can be achieved after user habits regarding appliance use are understood.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Most energy providers divide the energy tariff into high and low-price hours; therefore, scheduling an appliance to work an off-peak hour will significantly reduce electricity bills.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] User activity detection leads to the precise detection of appliances required for an activity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] If an appliance is active but not required for a user's current activity, it wastes energy and can be turned off to conserve energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The precise identification of user activities is necessary to achieve this method of energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation measures have primarily focused on technological innovations to improve efficiencies and financial incentives with theoretical explanations obtained from the mentioned analytical traditions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Existing buildings can improve energy efficiency by changing structural maintenance materials, adjusting the composition of air conditioning systems, selecting energy-saving equipment, and formulating subsidy policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These measures can improve users' thermal comfort and reduce buildings' environmental impact.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The selection of combinatorial optimization schemes that contain measures to guide and restrict users' behavior in addition to carrying out demand-side management can dynamically adjust energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] At the same time, economic means should enable users to change their behavior and achieve a low-carbon life.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Combination optimization and pricing incentives reduce building energy consumption and carbon emissions and reduce users' costs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Monitoring through energy audits can help in achieving energy efficiency in existing buildings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] An energy audit is an inspection and analysis of energy use in a system intending to reduce energy input without negatively affecting output.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy audits can determine specific opportunities for energy conservation and efficiency measures as well as determine cost-effective strategies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Training professionals typically accomplish this and can be part of some national programs discussed above.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Smartphone apps enables homeowners to complete relatively sophisticated energy audits themselves.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] For instance, smart thermostats can connect to standard HVAC systems to maintain energy-saving indoor temperatures.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In addition, data loggers can also be installed to monitor the interior temperature and humidity levels to provide a more precise understanding of the conditions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] If the data gathered is compared with the users' perceptions of comfort, more fine-tuning of the interiors can be implemented (e.g., increasing the temperature where A.C. is used to prevent over-cooling).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Building technologies and smart meters can allow commercial and residential energy users to visualize the impact their energy use can have in their workplaces or homes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Advanced real-time energy metering can help people save energy through their actions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Another approach towards energy conservation is the implementation of ECMs in commercial buildings, which often employ Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) experienced in energy performance contracting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This industry has been around since the 1970s and is more prevalent than ever today.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The US-based organization EVO (Efficiency Valuation Organization) has created a set of guidelines for ESCOs to adhere to in evaluating the savings achieved by ECMs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These guidelines are called the International Performance Measurement and Verification Protocol (IPMVP).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy efficiency can also be achieved by upgrading certain aspects of existing buildings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Making thermal improvements by adding insulation to crawl spaces and ensuring no leaks achieves an efficient building envelope, reducing the need for mechanical systems to heat and cool the space.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] High-performance insulation is also supported by adding double/triple-glazed windows to minimize heat transmission.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] A window windcatcher can reduce the total energy use of a building by 23.3%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Paint colors and new paint technologies can conserve energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation through users' behaviors requires understanding household occupants' lifestyle, social, and behavioral factors in analyzing energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Replacing existing appliances with newer and more efficient ones leads to energy efficiency as less energy is wasted throughout.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Overall, energy efficiency behaviors are identified more with one-time, cost-incurring investments in efficient appliances and retrofits, while energy curtailment behaviors include repetitive, low-cost energy-saving efforts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] To identify and optimize residential energy use, conventional and behavioral economics, technology adoption theory and attitude-based decision-making, social and environmental psychology, and sociology must be analyzed.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The techno-economic and psychological literature analysis focuses on the individual attitude, behavior, and choice/context/external conditions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In contrast, the sociological literature relies more on the energy consumption practices shaped by the social, cultural, and economic factors in a dynamic setting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Many steps can be taken toward energy conservation and efficiency when designing new buildings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In passive solar building designs, windows, walls, and floors are made to collect, store, and distribute solar energy in the form of heat in the winter and reject solar heat in the summer.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The key to designing a passive solar building is to best take advantage of the local climate.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Elements to be considered include window placement and glazing type, thermal insulation, thermal mass, and shading.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Optimizing daylighting can decrease energy waste from incandescent bulbs, windows, and balconies, allow natural ventilation, reduce the need for heating and cooling, low flow mixers aid in water conservation, and upgrade to Energy star rated appliances consume less energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Designing a building according to LEED guidelines while incorporating smart home technology can help save a lot of energy and money in the long run.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Passive solar design techniques can be applied most easily to new buildings, but existing buildings can be retrofitted.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Mainly, energy conservation is achieved by modifying user habits or providing an energy-saving recommendation of curtailing an appliance or scheduling it to low-price energy tariff hours.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Besides changing user habits and appliance control, identifying irrelevant appliances concerning user activities in smart homes saves energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Smart home technology can advise users on energy-saving strategies according to their behavior, encouraging behavioral change that leads to energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This guidance includes reminders to turn off lights, leakage sensors to prevent plumbing issues, running appliances on off-peak hours, and smart sensors that save energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Such technology learns user-appliance activity patterns, gives a complete overview of various energy-consuming appliances, and can provide guidance to improve these patterns to contribute to energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It can strategically schedule appliances to the energy-efficient mode, or plan to work during off-peak hours.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This usually leads to appliance curtailment in which an appliance is either scheduled to work another time or is turned off.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Appliance curtailment involves appliance recognition, activity-appliances model, unattended appliance detection, and energy conservation service.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The appliance recognition module detects active appliances to identify the activities of smart home users.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] After identifying users' activities, the association between the functional appliances and user activities is established.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The unattended appliance detection module looks for active appliances but is unrelated to user activity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These functional appliances waste energy and can be turned off by providing recommendations to the user.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Users can give weight to certain appliances that increase user comfort while conserving energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy consumption models of energy consumption of appliances and the level of comfort they create can balance priorities among smart home comfort levels and energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] According to Kashimoto, Ogura, Yamamoto, Yasumoto, and Ito, the energy supply reduces based on the historical state of the appliance and increases according to the comfort level requirement of the user, leading to a targeted energy-saving ratio.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Scenarios-based energy consumption can be employed as a strategy for energy conservation, with each scenario encompassing a specific set of rules for energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Transporting people, goods, and services represented 29% of U.S. energy consumption in 2007.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The transportation sector also accounted for about 33% of U.S. carbon dioxide emissions in 2006, with highway vehicles accounting for about 84% of that, making transportation an essential target for addressing global climate change (E.I.A., 2008).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Land is developing at a faster rate than population growth, leading to urban sprawl and, therefore, high transportation energy intensity as more people need to commute longer distances to jobs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, the location of a building is essential in decreasing embodied emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In transportation, state and local efforts in energy conservation and efficiency measures tend to be more targeted and smaller in scale.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Zoning reforms that allow greater urban density and designs for walking and bicycling can greatly reduce energy consumed for transportation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Many Americans work in jobs that allow for remote work instead of commuting daily, which is a significant opportunity to conserve energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Intelligent transportation systems (ITS) provide a solution to traffic congestion and C.E.s caused by increased vehicles.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] ITS combines improvements in information technology and systems, communications, sensors, controllers, and advanced mathematical methods with the traditional world of transportation infrastructure.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It improves traffic safety and mobility, reduces environmental impact, promotes sustainable transportation, and increases productivity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] ITS can strengthen connection and cooperation between people, vehicles, roads, and the environment while improving road capacity, reducing traffic accidents, and improving transportation efficiency and safety by alleviating traffic congestion and reducing pollution.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It makes full use of traffic information as an application service, which can enhance the operational efficiency of existing traffic facilities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The most significant energy-saving potential is that there are the most problems in urban transportation in various countries, such as management systems, policies and regulations, planning, technology, operation, and management mechanism.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Improvements in one or several aspects will improve road transportation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Efficiency has a positive impact, which leads to the improvement of the urban traffic environment and efficiency.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In addition to ITS, transit-oriented development (T.O.D.) improves transportation in urban areas by emphasizing density, proximity to transit, diversity of uses, and streetscape design.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Density is important for optimizing location and is a way to cut down on driving.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Planners can regulate development rights by exchanging them from ecologically sensitive areas to growth-friendly zones according to density transfer procedures.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Distance is defined as the accessibility of rail and bus transits, which serve as deterrents for driving.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] For transit-oriented development to be feasible, transportation stops must be close to where people live.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Diversity refers to mixed-use areas that offer essential services close to homes and offices and include residential spaces for different socioeconomic categories, commercial and retail.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This creates a pedestrian shed where one area can meet people's everyday needs on foot.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Lastly, the streetscapes design involves minimal parking and walkable areas that calm traffic.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Generous parking incentivizes people to use cars, whereas minimal and expensive parking deters commuters.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] At the same time, streetscapes can be designed to incorporate bicycling lanes and designated bicycle paths and trails.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] People may commute by bicycle without being concerned about their bicycles becoming wet because of covered bicycle storage.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This encourages commuters to use bicycles rather than other modes of transportation and contributes to energy saving.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] People will be happy to walk a few blocks from a train stop if there are attractive, pedestrian-friendly outdoor spaces nearby with good lighting, park benches, outdoor tables at cafés, shade tree plantings, pedestrian courts that are blocked off to cars, and public internet connection.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Additionally, this strategy calms traffic, improving the intended pedestrian environment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] New urban planning schemes can be designed to improve connectivity in cities through networks of interconnected streets that spread out traffic flow, slow down vehicles, and make walking more pleasant.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] By dividing the number of road links by the number of road nodes, the connectivity index is calculated.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The higher the connectivity index, the greater the route choices and the better the pedestrian access.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Realizing the transportation impacts associated with buildings allows commuters to take steps toward energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Connectivity encourages energy-conserving behaviors as commuters use fewer cars, walk and bike more, and use public transportation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] For commuters who do not have the option of public transportation, smaller vehicles that are hybrid or have better mileage can be used.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Homeowners implementing ECMs in their residential buildings often start with an energy audit.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This is a way homeowners look at what areas of their homes are using, and possibly losing energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Residential energy auditors are accredited by the Building Performance Institute (BPI) or the Residential Energy Services Network (RESNET).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Homeowners can hire a professional or do it themselves or use a smartphone to help do an audit.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy conservation measures are often combined into larger guaranteed Energy Savings Performance Contracts to maximize energy savings while minimizing disruption to building occupants by coordinating renovations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Some ECMs cost less to implement yet return higher energy savings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Traditionally, lighting projects were a good example of "low hanging fruit" that could be used to drive implementation of more substantial upgrades to HVAC systems in large facilities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Smaller buildings might combine window replacement with modern insulation using advanced building foams to improve energy for performance.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy dashboard projects are a new kind of ECM that relies on the behavioral change of building occupants to save energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] When implemented as part of a program, case studies, such as that for the DC Schools, report energy savings up 30%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Under the right circumstances, open energy dashboards can even be implemented for free to improve upon these savings even more.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Consumers are often poorly informed of the savings of energy-efficient products.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] A prominent example of this is the energy savings that can be made by replacing an incandescent light bulb with a more modern alternative.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] When purchasing light bulbs, many consumers opt for cheap incandescent bulbs, failing to take into account their higher energy costs and lower lifespans when compared to modern compact fluorescent and LED bulbs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Although these energy-efficient alternatives have a higher upfront cost, their long lifespan and low energy use can save consumers a considerable amount of money.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The price of LED bulbs has also been steadily decreasing in the past five years due to improvements in semiconductor technology.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Many LED bulbs on the market qualify for utility rebates that further reduce the price of the purchase to the consumer.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Department of Energy state that widespread adoption of LED lighting over the next 20 years could result in about $265 billion worth of savings in United States energy costs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The research one must put into conserving energy is often too time-consuming and costly for the average consumer when there are cheaper products and technology available using today's fossil fuels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Some governments and NGOs are attempting to reduce this complexity with Eco-labels that make differences in energy efficiency easy to research while shopping.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] To provide the kind of information and support people need to invest money, time and effort in energy conservation, it is important to understand and link to people's topical concerns.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] For instance, some retailers argue that bright lighting stimulates purchasing.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] However, health studies have demonstrated that headache, stress, blood pressure, fatigue and worker error all generally increase with the common over-illumination present in many workplace and retail settings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It has been shown that natural daylighting increases productivity levels of workers, while reducing energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In warm climates where air conditioning is used, any household device that gives off heat will result in a larger load on the cooling system.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Items such as stoves, dishwashers, clothes dryers, hot water, and incandescent lighting all add heat to the home.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Low-power or insulated versions of these devices give off less heat for the air conditioning to remove.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The air conditioning system can also improve efficiency by using a heat sink that is cooler than the standard air heat exchanger, such as geothermal or water.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In cold climates, heating air and water is a major demand for household energy use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Significant energy reductions are possible by using different technologies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Heat pumps are a more efficient alternative to electrical resistance heaters for warming air or water.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] A variety of efficient clothes dryers are available, and the clothes lines requires no energy- only time.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Natural-gas (or bio-gas) condensing boilers and hot-air furnaces increase efficiency over standard hot-flue models.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Standard electric boilers can be made to run only at hours of the day when they are needed by means of a time switch.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In showers, a semi-closed-loop system could be used.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] New construction implementing heat exchangers can capture heat from wastewater or exhaust air in bathrooms, laundry, and kitchens.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In both warm and cold climate extremes, airtight thermal insulated construction is the largest factor determining the efficiency of a home.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Insulation is added to minimize the flow of heat to or from the home, but can be labor-intensive to retrofit to an existing home.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Although energy efficiency is expected to play a vital role in cost-effectively cutting energy demand, only a small part of its economic potential is exploited in Asia.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Governments have implemented a range of subsidies such as cash grants, cheap credit, tax exemptions, and co-financing with public-sector funds to encourage energy-efficiency initiatives across several sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Road transportation is the highest priority to achieve energy conservation effectively and reduce emissions, particularly since social and economic development has entered the "new norm" period.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Generally speaking, the government should make comprehensive plans for conservation and emissions reduction in the road transportation industry within the three dimensions of demand, structure, and technology.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] For example, encouraging trips using public transportation and new transportation modes such as car-sharing and increasing investment in new energy vehicles in structure reform, etc.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] At the end of 2006, the European Union (EU) pledged to cut its annual consumption of primary energy by 20% by 2020.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The EU Energy Efficiency Directive 2012 mandates energy efficiency improvements within the EU.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] As part of the EU's SAVE program, aimed at promoting energy efficiency and encouraging energy-saving behavior, the Boiler Efficiency Directive specifies minimum levels of efficiency for boilers using liquid or gaseous fuels.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] There is steady progress on energy regulation implementation in Europe, North America, and Asia, with the highest number of building energy standards being adopted and implemented.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Moreover, the performance of Europe is highly encouraging concerning energy standard activities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] They recorded the highest percentage of mandatory energy standards compared to the other five regions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In 2050, energy savings in Europe can reach 67% of the 2019 baseline scenario, amounting to a demand of 361 Mtoe in an "energy efficiency first" societal trend scenario.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] A condition is that there be no rebound effect, for otherwise the savings are 32% only or energy use may even increase by 42% if techno-economic potentials are not realized.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Germany has reduced its primary energy consumption by 11% from 1990 to 2015 and set itself goals of reducing it by 30% by the year 2030 and by 50% by the year 2050 in comparison to the level of 2008.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Petroleum Conservation Research Association (PCRA) is an Indian governmental body created in 1978 that engages in promoting energy efficiency and conservation in every walk of life.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In the recent past, PCRA has organised mass media campaigns in television, radio, and print media.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This is an impact-assessment survey by a third party that revealed that due to these larger campaigns by PCRA, the public's overall awareness level has gone up leading to the saving of fossil fuels worth crores of rupees, besides reducing pollution.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Bureau of Energy Efficiency is an Indian government organization created in 2001 that is responsible for promoting energy efficiency and conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Protection and Conservation of Natural Resources are done by Community Natural Resources Management (CNRM).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Supreme leader of Iran Ali Khamenei had regularly criticized energy administration and high fuel consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Since the 1973 oil crisis, energy conservation has been an issue in Japan.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] All oil-based fuel is imported, so domestic sustainable energy is being developed.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Conservation Center promotes energy efficiency in every aspect of Japan.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Public entities are implementing the efficient use of energy for industries and research.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] It includes projects such as the Top Runner Program.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In this project, new appliances are regularly tested on efficiency, and the most efficient ones are made the standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Middle East holds 40% of the world's crude oil reserves and 23% of its natural gas reserves.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Conservation of domestic fossil fuels is, therefore, a legitimate priority for the Gulf countries, given domestic needs as well as the global market for these products.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Energy subsidies are the chief barrier to conservation in the Gulf.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Residential electricity prices can be a tenth of U.S. rates.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] As a result, increased tariff revenues from gas, electricity, and water sales would encourage investment in natural gas exploration and production and generation capacity, helping to alleviate future shortages.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Households in the MENA region are responsible for 53% of energy use in Saudi Arabia and 57% of the UAE's ecological footprint.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] This is partially due to poorly designed and constructed buildings, mainly under a cheap energy model that has left them without contemporary control technology or even proper insulation and efficient appliances.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Building energy consumption can be cut by 20% under a combination of insulation, efficient windows and appliances, shading, reflective roofing, and a host of automated controls that adjust energy use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Governments could also set minimum energy efficiency and water use standards on importing appliances sold inside their countries, effectively banning the sale of inefficient air conditioners, dishwashers, and washing machines.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Administration of the laws would essentially be a function of national customs services.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Governments could go further, offering incentives – or mandates – that air conditioners of a certain age be replaced.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Since 2002 The Lebanese Center for Energy Conservation (LCEC) has been promoting the development of efficient and rational uses of energy and the use of renewable energy at the consumer level.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Until recently, Nepal has been focusing on the exploitation of its huge water resources to produce hydropower.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Demand-side management and energy conservation were not in the focus of government action.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In 2009, bilateral Development Cooperation between Nepal and the Federal Republic of Germany has agreed upon the joint implementation of the "Nepal Energy Efficiency Programme".
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The lead executing agencies for the implementation are the Water and Energy Commission Secretariat (WECS).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The aim of the program is the promotion of energy efficiency in policymaking, in rural and urban households as well as in the industry.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Due to the lack of a government organization that promotes energy efficiency in the country, the Federation of Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI) has established the Energy Efficiency Centre under his roof to promote energy conservation in the private sector.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Efficiency Centre is a non-profit initiative that is offering energy auditing services to the industries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The centre is also supported by Nepal Energy Efficiency Programme of Deutsche Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] A study conducted in 2012 found out that Nepalese industries could save 160,000-megawatt hours of electricity and 8,000 terajoules of thermal energy (like diesel, furnace oil, and coal) every year.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These savings are equivalent to annual energy cost cut of up to 6.4 Billion Nepalese Rupees.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] As a result of Nepal Economic Forum 2014, an economic reform agenda in the priority sectors was declared focusing on energy conservation among others.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In the energy reform agenda, the government of Nepal gave the commitment to introduce incentive packages in the budget of the fiscal year 2015/16 for industries that practices energy efficiency or use efficient technologies (incl. cogeneration).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In New Zealand the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Authority is the Government Agency responsible for promoting energy efficiency and conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Energy Management Association of New Zealand is a membership-based organization representing the New Zealand energy services sector, providing training and accreditation services with the aim of ensuring energy management services are credible and dependable.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In Nigeria, the Lagos State Government is encouraging Lagosians to imbibe an energy conservation culture.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In 2013, the Lagos State Electricity Board (LSEB) ran an initiative tagged "Conserve Energy, Save Money" under the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The initiative is designed to sensitize Lagosians around the theme of energy conservation by influencing their behavior through do-it-yourself tips.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In September 2013, Governor Babatunde Raji Fashola of Lagos State and the campaign ambassador, rapper Jude "MI" Abaga participated in the Governor's conference video call on the topic of energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] To get Lagosians started on energy conservation, solar lamps and energy-saving bulbs were also handed out.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In Kaduna State, the Kaduna Power Supply Company (KAPSCO) ran a program to replace all light bulbs in Public Offices; fitting energy-saving bulbs in place of incandescent bulbs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] KAPSCO is also embarking on an initiative to retrofit all conventional streetlights in the Kaduna Metropolis to LEDs which consume much less energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Sri Lanka currently consumes fossil fuels, hydro power, wind power, solar power and dendro power for their day to day power generation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Sri Lanka Sustainable Energy Authority is playing a major role regarding energy management and energy conservation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Today, most industries are requested to reduce their energy consumption by using renewable energy sources and optimizing their energy usage.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Turkey aims to decrease by at least 20% the amount of energy consumed per GDP of Turkey by 2023 (energy intensity).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is responsible for promoting energy efficiency in the United Kingdom.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The United States is currently the second-largest single consumer of energy, following China.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Department of Energy categorizes national energy use in four broad sectors: transportation, residential, commercial, and industrial.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] About half of U.S. energy consumption in the transportation and residential sectors is primarily controlled by individual consumers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] In the typical American home, space heating is the most significant energy use, followed by electrical technology (appliances, lighting, and electronics) and water heating.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Commercial and industrial energy expenditures are determined by businesses entities and other facility managers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] National energy policy has a significant effect on energy usage across all four sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Since the oil embargoes and price spikes of the 1970s, energy efficiency and conservation have been fundamental tenets of U.S. energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The scope of energy conservation and efficiency measures has been broadened throughout time by U.S. energy policies and programs, including federal and state legislation and regulatory actions, to include all economic sectors and all geographical areas of the nation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Lack of a national consensus on how to proceed interfered with developing a consistent and comprehensive approach.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Nevertheless, the Energy Policy Act of 2005 (EPAct05; 109th U.S.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Congress, 2005) contained many new energy conservation and efficiency provisions in the transportation, buildings, and electric power sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The most recent federal law to increase and broaden U.S. energy conservation and efficiency laws, programs, and practices is the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Over the next few decades, it is anticipated that EISA will significantly reduce energy use because it has more standards and targets than previous legislation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Both acts reinforce the importance of lighting and appliance efficiency programs, targeting an additional 70% lighting efficiency by 2020, introducing 45 new standards for appliances, and setting up new standards for vehicle fuel economy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The Federal Government is also promoting a new 30% model code for efficient building practices in the construction industry.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Additionally, according to the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ACEEE), the EISA's energy efficiency and conservation initiatives will cut carbon dioxide emissions by 9% in 2030.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] These requirements cover appliance and lighting efficiency, energy savings in homes, businesses, and public buildings, the effectiveness of industrial manufacturing facilities, and the efficiency of electricity supply and end use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Expectations are high for increased energy savings due to these initiatives, which have already started contributing to new federal, state, and local laws, programs, and practices across the U.S.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] The development and use of alternative transportation fuels (whose supply is expected to expand by 15% by 2022), renewable energy sources, and other clean energy technologies have also received more attention and financial incentives.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p01] Recent policies also emphasize growing the use of coal with carbon capture and sequestration, solar, wind, nuclear, and other clean energy sources.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Governments at the national, regional, and local levels may implement policies to promote energy efficiency.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Building energy rules can cover the energy consumption of an entire structure or specific building components, like heating and cooling systems.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] They represent some of the most frequently used instruments for energy efficiency improvements in buildings and can play an essential role in improving energy conservation in buildings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] There are multiple reasons for the growth of these policies and programs since the 2000s, including cost savings as energy prices increased, growing concern about the environmental impacts of energy use, and public health concerns.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The policies and programs related to energy conservation are critical to establishing safety and performance levels, assisting in consumer decision-making, and explicitly identifying energy-conserving and energy-efficient products.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Recent policies include new programs and regulatory incentives that call for electric and natural gas utilities to increase their involvement in delivering energy-efficiency products and services to their customers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The success of building energy regulation in effectively controlling energy consumption in the building sector will be, to a great extent, associated with the adopted energy performance indicator and the promoted energy assessment tools.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] It can help overcome significant market barriers and ensure cost-effective energy efficiency opportunities are incorporated into new buildings.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] This is crucial in emerging nations where new constructions are rapidly developing, and market and energy prices sometimes discourage efficient technologies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The building energy standards development and adoption showed that 42% of emerging developing countries surveyed have no energy standard in place, 20% have mandatory, 22% have mixed, and 16% proposed.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The major impediments to implementing building energy regulations for energy conservation and efficiency in the building sector are institutional barriers and market failures rather than technical problems, as pointed out by Nature Publishing Group (2008).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Among these, Santamouris (2005) includes a lack of owners' awareness of energy conservation benefits, building energy regulations benefits, insufficient awareness and training of property managers, builders, and engineers, and a lack of specialized professionals to ensure compliance.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Based on the above information, the development and adoption of building energy regulations, such as energy standards in developing countries, are still far behind compared to building energy regulation adoption and implementation in developed countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Building energy standards are starting to appear in Africa, Latin America, and Middle East regions, even though this is a new development going to the result obtained in this study.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The level of progress on energy regulation activities in Africa, Latin America, and the Middle East is increasing, given the higher number of energy standard proposals recorded in these regions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] According to the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors, several codes are being developed in developing countries with UNDP and GEF support.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] These typically include elemental and integrated routes to compliance, such as a fundamental method defining the performance requirements of specific building elements.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] However, they are still far behind in building energy regulation development, implementation, and compliance compared to developed nations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Also, decision-making regarding energy regulations is still from the government only, with little or no input from non-governmental entities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] As a result, lower energy regulation development is recorded in these regions compared to regions with integrated and consensus approaches.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Several North African nations, like Tunisia and Egypt, have programs relating to building energy standards, while Algeria and Morocco are now seeking to establish building energy standards, according to the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Similarly, Egypt's residential energy standard became law in 2005, and their commercial standard was anticipated to follow.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The standards provide minimal performance requirements for applications involving air conditioners and other appliances and elemental and integrated pathways.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] However, it was claimed that enforcement legislation was still required in 2005.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Additionally, Morocco launched a program in 2005 to create thermal energy requirements for construction, concentrating on the hospitality, healthcare, and communal housing industries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Energy standards are the primary way governments foster energy efficiency as a public good.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] A recognized standard-setting organization prepares a standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Standards developed by recognized organizations are often used as the basis for the development and updating of building codes.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] They allow innovative approaches and techniques to achieve effective energy use and optimum building performance.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Besides, it encourages cost-effective energy use of building components, including building envelope, lighting, HVAC, electrical installations, lift and escalator, and other equipment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Energy-efficiency standards have been expanded and strengthened for appliances, building equipment, and lighting.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] For example, appliances and equipment standards are being developed for a new range of devices, including reduction goals for "standby" power that keeps consumer electronic products in a ready-to-use mode.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Some devices require certain levels of energy performance from a car, building, appliance, or other technical equipment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] If the vehicle, building, appliance, or equipment does not meet these standards, there may be restrictions on its sale or rent.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] In the U.K., these are called "minimum energy efficiency standards" or MEES and were applied to privately rented accommodation in 2019.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Energy codes and standards are vital in setting minimum energy-efficient design and construction requirements.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Buildings should be developed following energy standards to save energy efficiently.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] They specify uniform requirements for new buildings, additions, and modifications.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] National organizations like the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers publish the standards (ASHRAE).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] State and municipal governments frequently use energy standards as the technical foundation for creating their energy regulations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Some energy standards are written in a mandatory and enforceable language, making it simple for governments to add the standards' provisions directly to their laws or regulations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) is a well-known example of a standard-making organization.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] This organization dates to the nineteenth century and is international in its membership (About ASHRAE 2018).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The Residential Energy Services Network is a crucial benchmark for energy reduction (RESNET).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The Home Energy Rating System (HERS) of RESNET, which is based on the International Code Council's (ICC) energy code, is used to rate home energy consumption with a standard numerical scale that examines factors in home energy use (About HERS 2018).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) has acknowledged the HERS assessment system as a national benchmark for evaluating energy efficiency.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The International Energy Conservation Code (IECC) of the ICC requires an energy rating index, and the main index used in the residential building sector is HERS.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The mortgage financing sector makes substantial use of the HERS index.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] A home's expected energy usage may impact the available mortgage funds based on the HERS score, with more energy-efficient, lower energy-using homes potentially qualifying for a better mortgage rate or amount.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Many governments require that a car, building, or piece of equipment be labeled with its energy performance.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] This allows consumers and customers to see the energy implications of their choices, but does not restrict their choices or regulate which products are available to choose from.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] It also does not enable easily comparing options (such as being able to filter by energy-efficiency in online stores) or have the best energy-conserving options accessible (such as energy-conserving options being available in the frequented local store).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Moreover, in this one trial the labeling was ineffective in shifting purchases towards more sustainable options.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Some countries employ energy or carbon taxes to motivate energy users to reduce their consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Carbon taxes can motivate consumption to shift to energy sources with fewer emissions of carbon dioxide, such as solar power, wind power, hydroelectricity or nuclear power while avoiding cars with combustion engines, jet fuel, oil, fossil gas and coal.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] On the other hand, taxes on all energy consumption can reduce energy use across the board while reducing a broader array of environmental consequences arising from energy production.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The state of California employs a tiered energy tax whereby every consumer receives a baseline energy allowance that carries a low tax.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] As for usage increases above that baseline, the tax increases drastically.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Such programs aim to protect poorer households while creating a larger tax burden for high energy consumers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Developing countries specifically are less likely to impose policy measures that slow carbon emissions as this would slow their economic development.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] These growing countries may be more likely to support their own economic growth and support their citizens rather than decreasing their carbon emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The following pros and cons of a carbon tax help one to see some of the potential effects of a carbon tax policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] Another aspect of promoting energy efficiency is using the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) voluntary building design standards.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] This program is supported by the US Green Building Council.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-conservation-p02] The "Energy and Atmosphere" Prerequisite applies to energy issues, it focuses on energy performance, renewable energy, and other.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In computer networking, **Energy-Efficient Ethernet** (**EEE**) is a set of enhancements to twisted-pair, twinaxial, backplane, and optical fiber Ethernet physical-layer variants that reduce power consumption during periods of low data activity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The intention is to reduce power consumption by at least half, while retaining full compatibility with existing equipment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), through the **IEEE 802.3az** task force, developed the standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The first study group had its call for interest in November 2006, and the official standards task force was authorized in May 2007.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The IEEE ratified the final standard in September 2010.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Some companies introduced technology to reduce the power required for Ethernet before the standard was ratified, using the name **Green Ethernet**.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Some energy-efficient switch integrated circuits were developed before the IEEE 802.3az Energy-Efficient Ethernet standard was finalized.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In 2005, all the network interface controllers in the United States (in computers, switches, and routers) used an estimated 5.3 terawatt-hours of electricity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] According to a researcher at the Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, Energy-Efficient Ethernet can potentially save an estimated US$450 million a year in energy costs in the US.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Most of the savings would come from homes (US$200 million) and offices (US$170 million), and the remaining US$80 million from data centers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The power reduction is accomplished in a few ways.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In Fast Ethernet and faster links, constant and significant energy is used by the physical layer as transmitters are active regardless of whether data is being sent.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] If they could be put into sleep mode when no data is being sent, that energy could be saved.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] When the controlling software or firmware decides that no data needs to be sent, it can issue a low-power idle (LPI) request to the Ethernet controller physical layer PHY.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The PHY will then send LPI symbols for a specified time onto the link, and then disable its transmitter.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Refresh signals are sent periodically to maintain link signaling integrity.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] When there is data to transmit, a normal IDLE signal is sent for a predetermined period of time.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] The data link is considered to be always operational, as the receive signal circuit remains active even when the transmit path is in sleep mode.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Green Ethernet technology was a superset of the 802.3az standard.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In addition to the link load power savings of Energy-Efficient Ethernet, Green Ethernet works in one of two ways.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] First, it detects link status, allowing each port on the switch to power down into a standby mode when a connected device, such as a computer, is not active.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Second, it detects cable length and adjusts the power used for transmission accordingly.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Standard switches provide enough power to send a signal up to 100 meters (330 ft).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] However, this is often unnecessary in the SOHO environment, where 5 to 10 meters (16 to 33 ft) of cabling are typical between rooms.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Moreover, small data centers can also benefit from this approach since the majority of cabling is confined to a single room with a few meters of cabling among servers and switches.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In addition to the pure power-saving benefits of Green Ethernet, backing off the transmit power on shorter cable runs reduces alien crosstalk and improves the overall performance of the cabling system.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Green Ethernet also encompasses the use of more efficient circuitry in Ethernet chips, and the use of offload engines on Ethernet interface cards intended for network servers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] In April 2008, the term was used for switches, and, in July 2008, used with wireless routers that featured user-selectable off periods for Wi-Fi to further reduce energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-efficient-ethernet] Projected power savings of up to 80 percent were predicted using Green Ethernet switches, translating into a longer product life due to reduced heat.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy sector emits more greenhouse gas worldwide than any other sector.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Therefore, energy policies are closely related to climate policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] These decisions affect how high the greenhouse gas emissions by that country are.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy sector is the largest contributor to global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, accounting for over 73% of total CO2 emissions worldwide.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] As a result, energy policies are intrinsically linked to climate policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Decisions regarding energy infrastructure—such as reliance on coal versus renewables—determine a nation's carbon footprint and its ability to meet international climate commitments (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] For instance, countries investing in wind, solar, and nuclear energy typically achieve faster decarbonization than those dependent on coal and oil.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Given the urgency of climate change, many nations are transitioning toward low-carbon energy systems through policies like the U.S.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Inflation Reduction Act (IRA) and the European Green Deal, which incentivize renewable energy adoption while reducing fossil fuel dependence.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Access to energy is critical for basic social needs, such as lighting, heating, cooking, and healthcare.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Given the importance of energy, the price of energy has a direct effect on jobs, economic productivity, business competitiveness, and the cost of goods and services.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Frequently the dominant issue of energy policy is the risk of supply-demand mismatch (see: energy crisis).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Current energy policies also address environmental issues (see: climate change), particularly challenging because of the need to reconcile global objectives and international rules with domestic needs and laws.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The "human dimensions" of energy use are of increasing interest to business, utilities, and policymakers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Using the social sciences to gain insights into energy consumer behavior can help policymakers to make better decisions about broad-based climate and energy options.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] This could facilitate more efficient energy use, renewable-energy commercialization, and carbon-emission reductions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The attributes of energy policy may include legislation, international treaties, incentives to investment, guidelines for energy conservation, taxation and other public policy techniques.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Economic and energy modelling can be used by governmental or inter-governmental bodies as an advisory and analysis tool.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy planning is more detailed than energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Some governments state an explicit energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Others do not but in any case, each government practices some type of energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] A national energy policy comprises a set of measures involving that country's laws, treaties and agency directives.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] There are a number of elements that are contained in a national energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policy sometimes dominates and sometimes is dominated by other government policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] For example energy policy may dominate, supplying free coal to poor families and schools thus supporting social policy, but thus causing air pollution and so impeding heath policy and environmental policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] On the other hand energy policy may be dominated by defense policy, for example some counties started building expensive nuclear power plants to supply material for bombs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Or defense policy may be dominated for a while, eventually resulting in stranded assets, such as Nord Stream 2.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policy is closely related to climate change policy because totalled worldwide the energy sector emits more greenhouse gas than other sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policy decisions are sometimes not taken democratically.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] In 2019, some companies "have committed to set climate targets across their operations and value chains aligned with limiting global temperature rise to 1.5°C above pre-industrial levels and reaching net-zero emissions by no later than 2050".
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Corporate power purchase agreements can kickstart renewable energy projects, but the energy policies of some countries do not allow or discourage them.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Nuclear energy policies often include the regulation of energy use and standards relating to the nuclear fuel cycle.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Other measures include efficiency standards, safety regulations, emission standards, fiscal policies, and legislation on energy trading, transport of nuclear waste and contaminated materials, and their storage.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Governments might subsidize nuclear energy and arrange international treaties and trade agreements about the import and export of nuclear technology, electricity, nuclear waste, and uranium.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Since about 2001 the term nuclear renaissance has been used to refer to a possible nuclear power industry revival, but nuclear electricity generation in 2012 was at its lowest level since 1999.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Since then it had increased back to 2,653 TWh in 2021, a level last seen in 2006.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The share of nuclear power in electricity production however is at a historic low and now below 10% down from a maximum of 17.5% in 1996.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Following the March 2011 Fukushima I nuclear accidents, China, Germany, Switzerland, Israel, Malaysia, Thailand, United Kingdom, and the Philippines are reviewing their nuclear power programs.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Indonesia and Vietnam still plan to build nuclear power plants.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Thirty-one countries operate nuclear power stations, and there are a considerable number of new reactors being built in China, South Korea, India, and Russia.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] As of June 2011, countries such as Australia, Austria, Denmark, Greece, Ireland, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Luxembourg, Malta, Portugal, Israel, Malaysia, and Norway have no nuclear power stations and remain opposed to nuclear power.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Since nuclear energy and nuclear weapons technologies are closely related, military aspirations can act as a factor in energy policy decisions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The fear of nuclear proliferation influences some international nuclear energy policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Public policy has a role to play in renewable energy commercialization because the free market system has some fundamental limitations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] As the Stern Review points out: "In a liberalised energy market, investors, operators and consumers should face the full cost of their decisions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] But this is not the case in many economies or energy sectors.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Many policies distort the market in favour of existing fossil fuel technologies." The International Solar Energy Society has stated that "historical incentives for the conventional energy resources continue even today to bias markets by burying many of the real societal costs of their use".
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Fossil-fuel energy systems have different production, transmission, and end-use costs and characteristics than do renewable energy systems, and new promotional policies are needed to ensure that renewable systems develop as quickly and broadly as is socially desirable.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Lester Brown states that the market "does not incorporate the indirect costs of providing goods or services into prices, it does not value nature's services adequately, and it does not respect the sustainable-yield thresholds of natural systems".
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] It also favors the near term over the long term, thereby showing limited concern for future generations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Tax and subsidy shifting can help overcome these problems, though is also problematic to combine different international normative regimes regulating this issue.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The People's Republic of China is both the world's largest energy consumer and the largest industrial country.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] China is currently the world's largest emitter of greenhouse gases, and coal in China is a major cause of global warming.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] China is also the world's largest renewable energy producer, and the largest producer of hydroelectricity, solar power and wind power in the world.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy policy of China is connected to its industrial policy, where the goals of China's industrial production dictate its energy demand management.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Being a country that depends heavily on foreign petroleum import for both domestic consumption and as raw materials for light industry manufacturing, electrification is a huge component of the Chinese national energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy policy of India is to increase the locally produced energy in India and reduce energy poverty, with more focus on developing alternative sources of energy, particularly nuclear, solar and wind energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Net energy import dependency was 40.9% in 2021-22.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The primary energy consumption in India grew by 13.3% in FY2022-23 and is the third biggest with 6% global share after China and USA.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] In 2018, India's net imports are nearly 205.3 million tons of crude oil and its products, 26.3 Mtoe of LNG and 141.7 Mtoe coal totaling to 373.3 Mtoe of primary energy which is equal to 46.13% of total primary energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] India is largely dependent on fossil fuel imports to meet its energy demands – by 2030, India's dependence on energy imports is expected to exceed 53% of the country's total energy consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] India's energy policy increasingly emphasizes energy transition and decarbonization strategies, particularly in sectors such as transportation.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] According to a report by The Energy and Resources Institute (TERI), the country is focusing on electric mobility, alternative fuels, and policy-driven approaches to reduce carbon emissions and improve long-term energy sustainability.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy policy of the European Union focuses on energy security, sustainability, and integrating the energy markets of member states.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] An increasingly important part of it is climate policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] A key energy policy adopted in 2009 is the 20/20/20 objectives, binding for all EU Member States.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The target involved increasing the share of renewable energy in its final energy use to 20%, reduce greenhouse gases by 20% and increase efficient energy use by 20%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] After this target was met, new targets for 2030 were set at a 55% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2030 as part of the European Green Deal.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Since the Russian invasion of Ukraine has begun, the EU's energy policy turned more towards energy security in their REPowerEU policy package, which boosts both renewable deployment and fossil fuel infrastructure for alternative suppliers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Russia's energy policy is presented in the government's *Energy Strategy* document, first approved in 2000, which sets out the government's policy to 2020 (later extended to 2030).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The Energy Strategy outlines several key priorities: increased energy efficiency, reducing the impact on the environment, sustainable development, energy development and technological development, as well as improved effectiveness and competitiveness.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Russia's greenhouse gas emissions are large because of its energy policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Russia is rich in natural energy resources and is one of the world's energy superpowers.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Russia is the world's leading net energy exporter, and was a major supplier to the European Union until the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Russia has signed and ratified the Kyoto Protocol and Paris Agreement.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Numerous scholars posit that Russia uses its energy exports as a foreign policy instrument towards other countries.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy policy of the United Kingdom refers to the United Kingdom's efforts towards reducing energy intensity, reducing energy poverty, and maintaining energy supply reliability.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The United Kingdom has had success in this, though energy intensity remains high.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] There is an ambitious goal to reduce carbon dioxide emissions in future years, but it is unclear whether the programmes in place are sufficient to achieve this objective.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Regarding energy self-sufficiency, UK policy does not address this issue, other than to concede historic energy security is currently ceasing to exist (due to the decline of North Sea oil production).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The United Kingdom historically has a good policy record of encouraging public transport links with cities, despite encountering problems with high speed trains, which have the potential to reduce dramatically domestic and short-haul European flights.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The policy also encourages the uptake of electric vehicles, options which represent viable means to moderate rising transport fossil fuel consumption.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Regarding renewable energy, the United Kingdom has goals for wind and tidal energy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The 2007 White Paper on Energy set a target that 20% of the UK's energy must come from renewable sources by 2020.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy markets are regulated by the Office of Gas and Electricity Markets (Ofgem).
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Areas of focus for energy policy by the UK government have changed since the Electricity Act 1989 and the Gas Act 1986 privatised these utilities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The policy focuses of successive UK governments since the full liberalisation of gas and electricity markets in 1998 and 1999 have included managing energy prices, decarbonisation, the rollout of smart meters, and improving the energy efficiency of the country's building stock.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The energy policy of the United States is determined by federal, state, and local entities.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Federal Energy policy is principally led by the U.S.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policy intersects closely with decarbonization, climate policy, and environmental policy.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policy spans issues of decarbonization, energy production, distribution, consumption, and modes of use, such as building codes, mileage standards, and commuting policies.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] U.S. energy policy may be addressed via legislation, regulation, court decisions, public participation, and other techniques.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Major federal energy policy acts were passed in 1974, 1992, 2005, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2020, 2021, and 2022, although energy-related policies have appeared in many other bills.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] The most significant recent bills include the Biden Administration Inflation Reduction Act as well as the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law.
[src:one-watt-initiative/energy-policy] Energy policies vary by country, see tables below.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The **One Watt Initiative** is an energy-saving initiative by the International Energy Agency (IEA) to reduce standby power use by any appliance to no more than one watt in 2010, and 0.5 watts in 2013.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The initiative has given rise to regulations in many countries and regions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] Standby power, informally called *vampire* or *phantom power,* refers to the electricity many appliances consume while they are switched off or in sleep mode.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The typical standby power per appliance is low (typically less than 25 W), but, when multiplied by the billions of appliances in houses and in commercial buildings, standby losses represent a significant fraction of total world electricity use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] According to Alan Meier, a staff scientist at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, standby power accounted for as much as 10% of household power consumption before the One Watt Initiative proposals were implemented as regulations.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] A study in France found that standby power accounted for 7% of total residential consumption, and other studies put the proportion of consumption due to standby power at 13%.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The IEA estimated in 2007 that standby power use produced 1% of the world's carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] To put the figure into context, total air travel contributes less than 3% of global CO2 emissions.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] Standby power can be reduced by technological means, reducing power used without affecting functionality, and by changing users' operating procedures.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The One Watt Initiative was launched by the IEA in 1999 to ensure through international cooperation that by 2010 all new appliances sold in the world use only one watt in standby mode.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] This would reduce CO2 emissions by 50 million tons in the OECD countries alone by 2010; the equivalent to removing 18 million cars from the roads.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] By 2005, South Korea and Australia had introduced the one watt benchmark in all new electrical devices, and according to the IEA other countries, notably Japan and China, had undertaken "strong measures" to reduce standby power use.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] In July 2007, California's 2005 appliance standards came into effect, limiting external power supply standby power consumption to 0.5 watts.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] On 6 January 2010, the European Commission's EC Regulation 1275/2008 came into force regulating requirements for standby and "off mode" electric power consumption of electrical and electronic household and office equipment.
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] The regulations mandate that from 6 January 2010 "off mode" and standby power shall not exceed 1 W, "standby-plus" power (providing information or status display in addition to possible reactivation function) shall not exceed 2 W (these figures are halved on 6 January 2013).
[src:one-watt-initiative/one-watt-initiative] Equipment must, where appropriate, provide an off mode and/or standby mode when the equipment is connected to the mains power source.
